Exghost

Target IP: 192.168.209.183

Can you exfiltrate the flags?

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: FTP on port 21, and HTTP on port 80. I will start enumeration with the application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this HTTP application. The HTTP status code of 403 is returned; meaning I do not have the permission to view the web content.


Doing a directory search shows an interesting directory called /uploads.


And browsing to /uploads returns the same 403 HTTP response. I tried to bypass this using a few techniques such as changing HTTP method, modifying HTTP header, etc, but I had no luck.


While performing enumeration against the HTTP application, I ran the command hydra -C /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Passwords/Default-Credentials/ftp-betterdefaultpasslist.txt ftp://192.168.209.183 -t 4 to perform bruteforcing against the FTP application. This turned out to be successful as there is a valid credential user:system.


Using the credential user:system to login to FTP, I downloaded the one file called backup. This file is of type PCAP.


After viewing the contents of the PCAP file, I found an image. But this image did not lead to anything else. I did find a directory called /exiftest.php which can be useful. But I found something more interesting, which is the ExifTool application and version 12.23. The parameter myFile is used for the file uploads.


And bingo! This application is vulnerable to RCE. I found the working exploit above at Github for this vulnerability. This repository contains the PoC and how to use the exploit. I made a copy of this exploit on my machine.

Exploitation


Using the public exploit, I created a payload for the reverse shell connection. The exploit was written to the image.jpg file. Now I have to upload this to the target machine.


And it worked! In the image above, the top terminal is where I upload the malicious reverse shell exploit that is inside the image.jpg file. The bottom terminal is where I gain a reverse shell connection. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


After transferring Linpeas to the target machine, I executed it to identify PE vectors. I did not find anything useful. I hit a brick wall at this point. However, I used the different recommended exploits and got a hit with the second exploit.


The target machine is vulnerable to the CVE-2021-4034. I transferred the exploit and ran it against the target machine to gain a root shell.
